[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey] All previous elections had been held on an at-large basis.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey] Five Federalists had been elected in the previous election.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey] For this election, New Jersey switched, for the first time, to using districts.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey] Three incumbents ran for re-election, of whom, two of whom lost to Democratic-Republicans.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey] The incumbents Jonathan Dayton (F) and Thomas Sinnickson (F) did not run for re-election.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/6th-united-states-congress] The **6th United States Congress** was the 6th meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, consisting of the Senate and the House of Representatives.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/6th-united-states-congress] It initially met at Congress Hall in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania and then was the first congress to meet in the new Capitol Building in Washington, D.C..
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/6th-united-states-congress] Its term was from March 4, 1799, to March 4, 1801, during the last two years of John Adams's presidency.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/6th-united-states-congress] It was the last Congress of the 18th century and the first to convene in the 19th.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/6th-united-states-congress] The apportionment of seats in House of Representatives was based on the 1790 United States census.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/6th-united-states-congress] Both chambers had a Federalist majority.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/6th-united-states-congress] This was the last Congress in which the Federalist Party controlled the presidency or either chamber of Congress.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/6th-united-states-congress] The count below identifies party affiliations at the beginning of the first session of this Congress, and includes members from vacancies and newly admitted states, when they were first seated.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/6th-united-states-congress] Changes resulting from subsequent replacements are shown below in the "Changes in membership" section.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/6th-united-states-congress] This list is arranged by chamber, then by state.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/6th-united-states-congress] Senators are listed by class, and representatives are listed by district.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/6th-united-states-congress] Senators were elected by the state legislatures every two years, with one-third beginning new six-year terms with each Congress.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/6th-united-states-congress] Preceding the names in the list below are Senate class numbers, which indicate the cycle of their election.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/6th-united-states-congress] In this Congress, Class 1 meant their term began in the last Congress, requiring re-election in 1802; Class 2 meant their term began in this Congress, requiring re-election in 1804; and Class 3 meant their term ended with this Congress, requiring re-election in 1800.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/6th-united-states-congress] The names of representatives elected statewide on the general ticket or otherwise at-large, are preceded by an "At-large," and the names of those elected from districts, whether plural or single member, are preceded by their district numbers.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/6th-united-states-congress] There were 7 resignations and 1 vacancy at the beginning of Congress.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/6th-united-states-congress] The Federalists had a 1-seat net loss and the Democratic-Republicans had a 2-seat net gain.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/6th-united-states-congress] The Federalists had a 4-seat net loss and the Democratic-Republicans had a 3-seat net gain.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/6th-united-states-congress] Lists of committees and their party leaders.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/aaron-kitchell] Born in Hanover Township in the Province of New Jersey, Kitchell attended the common schools and became a blacksmith.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/aaron-kitchell] He was elected to the Second Congress (March 4, 1791 – March 3, 1793) and to the Third Congress to fill the vacancy caused by the death of Abraham Clark and was reelected to the Fourth Congress, serving from January 29, 1795, to March 3, 1797.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/aaron-kitchell] He resumed his former business activities and was elected to the Sixth Congress (March 4, 1799 – March 3, 1801).
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/aaron-kitchell] He was then elected as a Democratic Republican to the U.S.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/aaron-kitchell] Kitchell died in Hanover Township on June 25, 1820, and was interred there in the churchyard of the Presbyterian Church.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The **Democratic-Republican Party**, known at the time as the **Republican Party** (also referred to by historians as the **Jeffersonian Republican Party**), was an American political party founded by Thomas Jefferson and James Madison in the early 1790s.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] It championed liberalism, republicanism, individual liberty, equal rights, separation of church and state, freedom of religion, anti-clericalism, emancipation of religious minorities, decentralization, free markets, free trade, and agrarianism.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] In foreign policy, it was hostile to Great Britain and sympathetic to the French Revolution and Napoleonic Wars.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The party became increasingly dominant after the 1800 elections as the opposing Federalist Party collapsed.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Increasing dominance over American politics also led to increasing factional splits within the party.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The Republicans splintered during the 1824 presidential election.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Those calling for a return to the older founding principles of the party were often referred to as "Democratic Republicans" (later Democrats) while those embracing the newer nationalist principles of "The American System" were often referred to as National Republicans (later Whigs).
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The Republican Party originated in Congress to oppose the nationalist and economically interventionist policies of Alexander Hamilton, who served as Secretary of the Treasury under President George Washington.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The Republicans and the opposing Federalist Party each became more cohesive during Washington's second term, partly as a result of the debate over the Jay Treaty.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Though he was defeated by Federalist John Adams in the 1796 presidential election, Jefferson and his Republican allies came into power following the 1800 elections.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] As president, Jefferson presided over a reduction in the national debt and government spending, and completed the Louisiana Purchase with France.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Madison succeeded Jefferson as president in 1809 and led the country during the largely inconclusive War of 1812 with Britain.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] After the war, Madison and his congressional allies established the Second Bank of the United States and implemented protective tariffs, marking a move away from the party's earlier emphasis on states' rights and a strict construction of the United States Constitution.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The Federalists collapsed after 1815, beginning a period known as the Era of Good Feelings.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Republicans were deeply committed to the principles of republicanism, which they feared were threatened by the aristocratic tendencies of the Federalists.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] During the 1790s, the party strongly opposed Federalist programs, including the national bank.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] After the War of 1812, Madison and many other party leaders came to accept the need for a national bank and federally funded infrastructure projects.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] In foreign affairs, the party advocated western expansion and tended to favor France over Britain, though the party's pro-French stance faded after Napoleon took power.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The Democratic-Republicans were strongest in the South and the western frontier, and weakest in New England.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] In the 1788–89 presidential election, the first such election following the ratification of the United States Constitution in 1788, George Washington won the votes of every member of the Electoral College.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Washington selected Thomas Jefferson as Secretary of State and Alexander Hamilton as Secretary of the Treasury, and he relied on James Madison as a key adviser and ally in Congress.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Hamilton implemented an expansive economic program, establishing the First Bank of the United States, and convincing Congress to assume the debts of state governments.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Hamilton pursued his programs in the belief that they would foster a prosperous and stable country.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] His policies engendered an opposition, chiefly concentrated in the Southern United States, that objected to Hamilton's Anglophilia and accused him of unduly favoring well-connected wealthy Northern merchants and speculators.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Madison emerged as the leader of the congressional opposition while Jefferson, who declined to publicly criticize Hamilton while both served in Washington's Cabinet, worked behind the scenes to stymie Hamilton's programs.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Jefferson and Madison, leading an Anti-Administration group, established the *National Gazette*, a newspaper which recast national politics not as a battle between Federalists and Anti-Federalists, but as a debate between aristocrats and republicans.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] In the 1792 election, Washington effectively ran unopposed for president, but Jefferson and Madison backed New York Governor George Clinton's unsuccessful attempt to unseat Vice President John Adams.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Political leaders on both sides were reluctant to label their respective faction as a political party, but distinct and consistent voting blocs emerged in Congress by the end of 1793.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Jefferson's followers became known as the Republicans (or sometimes as the Democratic-Republicans) and Hamilton's followers (the Pro-Administration group) became the Federalists.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] While economic policies were the original motivating factor in the growing partisan split, foreign policy became even more important as war broke out between Great Britain (favored by Federalists) and France, which Republicans favored until 1799.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Partisan tensions escalated as a result of the Whiskey Rebellion and Washington's subsequent denunciation of the Democratic-Republican Societies, a type of new local political societies that favored democracy and generally supported the Jeffersonian position.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Historians use the term "Democratic-Republican" to describe these new organizations, but that name was rarely used at the time.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] They usually called themselves "Democratic", "Republican", "True Republican", "Constitutional", "United Freeman", "Patriotic", "Political", "Franklin", or "Madisonian".
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The ratification of the Jay Treaty with Britain further inflamed partisan warfare, resulting in a hardening of the divisions between the Federalists and the Republicans.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] By 1795–96, election campaigns—federal, state and local—were waged primarily along partisan lines between the two national parties, although local issues continued to affect elections, and party affiliations remained in flux.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] As Washington declined to seek a third term, the 1796 presidential election became the first contested president election.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Having retired from Washington's Cabinet in 1793, Jefferson had left the leadership of the Democratic-Republicans in Madison's hands.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Nonetheless, the Democratic-Republican congressional nominating caucus chose Jefferson as the party's presidential nominee, in the belief that he would be the party's strongest candidate; the caucus chose Senator Aaron Burr of New York as Jefferson's running mate.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Meanwhile, an informal caucus of Federalist leaders nominated a ticket of John Adams and Thomas Pinckney.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Though the candidates themselves largely stayed out of the fray, supporters of the candidates waged an active campaign; Federalists attacked Jefferson as a Francophile and atheist, while the Democratic-Republicans accused Adams of being an anglophile and a monarchist.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Ultimately, Adams won the presidency by a narrow margin, garnering 71 electoral votes to 68 for Jefferson, who became the vice president.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Shortly after Adams took office, he dispatched a group of envoys to seek peaceful relations with France, which had begun seizing American merchantmen trading with Britain after the ratification of the Jay Treaty.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The failure of talks, and the French demand for bribes in what became known as the XYZ Affair, outraged the American public and led to the Quasi-War, an undeclared naval war between France and the United States.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The Federalist-controlled Congress passed measures to expand the American military and also pushed through the Alien and Sedition Acts.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] These acts restricted speech critical of the government while also implementing stricter naturalization requirements.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Numerous journalists and other individuals aligned with the Democratic-Republicans were prosecuted under the Sedition Act, sparking a backlash against the Federalists.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Meanwhile, Jefferson and Madison drafted the Kentucky and Virginia Resolutions, which held that state legislatures could determine the constitutionality of federal laws.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] In the 1800 presidential election, the Democratic-Republicans once again nominated a ticket of Jefferson and Burr.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Shortly after a Federalist caucus re-nominated President Adams on a ticket with Charles Cotesworth Pinckney, Adams dismissed two Hamilton allies from his Cabinet, leading to an open break between the two key figures in the Federalist Party.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Though the Federalist Party united against Jefferson's candidacy and waged an effective campaign in many states, the Democratic-Republicans won the election by winning most Southern electoral votes and carrying the crucial state of New York.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] A significant element in the party's success in New York City, Philadelphia, Baltimore and other east-coast cities were United Irish exiles, and other Irish immigrants, whom the Federalists regarded with distinct suspicion.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Among these was William Duane who in his newspaper, the *Philadelphia Aurora*, exposed the details of the Ross Bill, by means of which the Federalist-controlled Congress sought to establish a closed-door Grand Committee with powers to disqualify College electors.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Adams was to name Duane one of the three or four men most responsible for his eventual defeat.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Jefferson and Burr both finished with 73 electoral votes, more than Adams or Pinckney, necessitating a contingent election between Jefferson and Burr in the House of Representatives.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Burr declined to take his name out of consideration, and the House deadlocked as most Democratic-Republican congressmen voted for Jefferson and most Federalists voted for Burr.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Preferring Jefferson to Burr, Hamilton helped engineer Jefferson's election on the 36th ballot of the contingent election.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Ideology played a central role with a Jeffersonian "left" supporting the French Revolution, versus a Federalist "right" opposing it.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Despite the intensity of the 1800 election, the transition of power from the Federalists to the Democratic-Republicans was peaceful.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] In his inaugural address, Jefferson indicated that he would seek to reverse many Federalist policies, but he also emphasized reconciliation, noting that "every difference of opinion is not a difference of principle".
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Gallatin persuaded Jefferson to retain the First Bank of the United States, a major part of the Hamiltonian program, but other Federalist policies were scrapped.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Jefferson and his Democratic-Republican allies eliminated the whiskey excise and other taxes, shrank the army and the navy, repealed the Alien and Sedition Acts, and pardoned all ten individuals who had been prosecuted under the acts.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] With the repeal of Federalist laws and programs, many Americans had little contact with the federal government in their daily lives, with the exception of the postal service.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Partly as a result of these spending cuts, Jefferson lowered the national debt from $83 million to $57 million between 1801 and 1809.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Though he was largely able to reverse Federalist policies, Federalists retained a bastion of power on the Supreme Court; Marshall Court rulings continued to reflect Federalist ideals until Chief Justice Marshall's death in the 1830s.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] In the Supreme Court case of *Marbury v.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Madison*, the Marshall Court established the power of judicial review, through which the judicial branch had the final word on the constitutionality of federal laws.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] By the time Jefferson took office, Americans had settled as far west as the Mississippi River.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Many in the United States, particularly those in the west, favored further territorial expansion, and especially hoped to annex the Spanish province of Louisiana.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] In early 1803, Jefferson dispatched James Monroe to France to join ambassador Robert Livingston on a diplomatic mission to purchase New Orleans.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] To the surprise of the American delegation, Napoleon offered to sell the entire territory of Louisiana for $15 million.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] After Secretary of State James Madison gave his assurances that the purchase was well within even the strictest interpretation of the Constitution, the Senate quickly ratified the treaty, and the House immediately authorized funding.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The Louisiana Purchase nearly doubled the size of the United States, and Treasury Secretary Gallatin was forced to borrow from foreign banks to finance the payment to France.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] By 1804, Vice President Burr had thoroughly alienated Jefferson, and the Democratic-Republican presidential nominating caucus chose George Clinton as Jefferson's running mate for the 1804 presidential election.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] That same year, Burr challenged Hamilton to a duel after taking offense to a comment allegedly made by Hamilton; Hamilton died in the subsequent duel.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Bolstered by a superior party organization, Jefferson won the 1804 election in a landslide over Federalist candidate Charles Cotesworth Pinckney.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] In 1807, as the Napoleonic Wars continued, the British government announced the Orders in Council, which called for a blockade on French-controlled ports.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] In response to subsequent British and French searches of American shipping, the Jefferson administration passed the Embargo Act of 1807, which cut off American trade with Europe.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The embargo proved unpopular and difficult to enforce, especially in Federalist-leaning New England, and expired at the end of Jefferson's second term.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Jefferson declined to seek a third term in the 1808 presidential election, but helped Madison triumph over George Clinton and James Monroe at the party's congressional nominating caucus.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Madison won the general election in a landslide over Pinckney.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] As attacks on American shipping continued after Madison took office, both Madison and the broader American public moved towards war.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Public resentment towards Britain led to the election of a new generation of Democratic-Republican leaders, including Henry Clay and John C.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Calhoun, who championed high tariffs, federally funded internal improvements and a jingoistic attitude towards Britain.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] On June 1, 1812, Madison asked Congress for a declaration of war.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The declaration was passed largely along sectional and party lines, with intense opposition coming from the Federalists and some other congressmen from the Northeast.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] For many who favored war, national honor was at stake; John Quincy Adams wrote that the only alternative to war was "the abandonment of our right as an independent nation." George Clinton's nephew, DeWitt Clinton, challenged Madison in the 1812 presidential election.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Though Clinton assembled a formidable coalition of Federalists and anti-Madison Democratic-Republicans, Madison won a close election.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Madison initially hoped for a quick end to the War of 1812, but the war got off to a disastrous start as multiple American invasions of Canada were defeated.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The United States had more military success in 1813, and American troops under William Henry Harrison defeated Tecumseh's confederacy in the Battle of the Thames in 1814, crushing Indian resistance to U.S. expansion.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Britain shifted troops to North America in 1814 following Napoleon's abdication, and British forces captured and burnt Washington in August 1814.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] In early 1815, Madison learned that his negotiators in Europe had signed the Treaty of Ghent, ending the war without major concessions by either side.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Though it had no effect on the treaty, Andrew Jackson's victory in the January 1815 Battle of New Orleans ended the war on a triumphant note.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Napoleon's defeat at the Battle of Waterloo in June 1815 brought a final end to the Napoleonic Wars and European interference with American shipping.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] With Americans celebrating a successful "second war of independence", the Federalist Party slid towards national irrelevance.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] In his first term, Madison and his allies had largely hewed to Jefferson's domestic agenda of low taxes and a reduction of the national debt, and Congress allowed the national bank's charter to expire during Madison's first term.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The challenges of the War of 1812 led many Democratic-Republicans to reconsider the role of the federal government.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] When the 14th Congress convened in December 1815, Madison proposed the re-establishment of the national bank, increased spending on the army and the navy, and a tariff designed to protect American goods from foreign competition.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] At the party's 1816 congressional nominating caucus, Secretary of State James Monroe defeated Secretary of War William H.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The Federalists offered little opposition in the 1816 presidential election and Monroe won in a landslide election.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Monroe believed that the existence of political parties was harmful to the United States, and he sought to usher in the end of the Federalist Party by avoiding divisive policies and welcoming ex-Federalists into the fold.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Monroe favored infrastructure projects to promote economic development and, despite some constitutional concerns, signed bills providing federal funding for the National Road and other projects.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Partly due to the mismanagement of national bank president William Jones, the country experienced a prolonged economic recession known as the Panic of 1819.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The panic engendered a widespread resentment of the national bank and a distrust of paper money that would influence national politics long after the recession ended.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Despite the ongoing economic troubles, the Federalists failed to field a serious challenger to Monroe in the 1820 presidential election, and Monroe won re-election essentially unopposed.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] During the proceedings over the admission of Missouri Territory as a state, Congressman James Tallmadge, Jr. of New York "tossed a bombshell into the Era of Good Feelings" by proposing amendments providing for the eventual exclusion of slavery from Missouri.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The amendments sparked the first major national slavery debate since the ratification of the Constitution, and instantly exposed the sectional polarization over the issue of slavery.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Northern Democratic-Republicans formed a coalition across partisan lines with the remnants of the Federalist Party in support of the amendments, while Southern Democratic-Republicans were almost unanimously against such the restrictions.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Thomas of Illinois proposed a compromise, in which Missouri would be admitted as a slave state, but slavery would be excluded in the remaining territories north of the parallel 36°30′ north.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] A bill based on Thomas's proposal became law in April 1820.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] By 1824, the Federalist Party had largely collapsed as a national party, and the 1824 presidential election was waged by competing members of the Democratic-Republican Party.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The party's congressional nominating caucus was largely ignored, and candidates were instead nominated by state legislatures.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Secretary of State John Quincy Adams, former Speaker of the House Henry Clay, Secretary of the Treasury William Crawford, and General Andrew Jackson emerged as the major candidates in the election.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The regional strength of each candidate played an important role in the election; Adams was popular in New England, Clay and Jackson were strong in the West, and Jackson and Crawford competed for the South.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] As no candidate won a majority of the electoral vote in the 1824 election, the House of Representatives held a contingent election to determine the president.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Clay personally disliked Adams but nonetheless supported him in the contingent election over Crawford, who opposed Clay's nationalist policies, and Jackson, whom Clay viewed as a potential tyrant.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] With Clay's backing, Adams won the contingent election.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] After Clay accepted appointment as Secretary of State, Jackson's supporters claimed that Adams and Clay had reached a "Corrupt Bargain" in which Adams promised Clay the appointment in return for Clay's support in the contingent election.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Jackson, who was deeply angered by the result of the contingent election, returned to Tennessee, where the state legislature quickly nominated him for president in the 1828 election.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Adams shared Monroe's goal of ending partisan conflict, and his Cabinet included individuals of various ideological and regional backgrounds.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] In his 1825 annual message to Congress, Adams presented a comprehensive and ambitious agenda, calling for major investments in internal improvements as well as the creation of a national university, a naval academy, and a national astronomical observatory.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] His requests to Congress galvanized the opposition, spurring the creation of an anti-Adams congressional coalition consisting of supporters of Jackson, Crawford, and Vice President Calhoun.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Following the 1826 elections, Calhoun and Martin Van Buren (who brought along many of Crawford's supporters) agreed to throw their support behind Jackson in the 1828 election.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] In the press, the two major political factions were referred to as "Adams Men" and "Jackson Men".
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The Jacksonians formed an effective party apparatus that adopted many modern campaign techniques and emphasized Jackson's popularity and the supposed corruption of Adams and the federal government.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Though Jackson did not articulate a detailed political platform in the same way that Adams did, his coalition was united in opposition to Adams's reliance on government planning and tended to favor the opening of Native American lands to white settlement.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Ultimately, Jackson won 178 of the 261 electoral votes and just under 56 percent of the popular vote.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Jackson won 50.3 percent of the popular vote in the free states and 72.6 percent of the vote in the slave states.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The election marked the permanent end of the Era of Good Feelings and the start of the Second Party System.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The dream of non-partisan politics, shared by Monroe, Adams, and many earlier leaders, was shattered, replaced with Van Buren's ideal of partisan battles between legitimated political parties.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] In the 1790s, political parties were new in the United States and people were not accustomed to having formal names for them.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] There was no single official name for the Democratic-Republican Party, but party members generally called themselves Republicans and voted for what they called the "Republican party", "republican ticket" or "republican interest".
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Jefferson and Madison often used the terms "republican" and "Republican party" in their letters.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The term "Democratic-Republican" was used by contemporaries only occasionally, but is used by modern political scientists.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Historians often refer to the "Jeffersonian Republicans".
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The term "Democratic Party" was first used pejoratively by Federalist opponents.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The Democratic-Republican Party saw itself as a champion of republicanism and denounced the Federalists as supporters of monarchy and aristocracy.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Ralph Brown writes that the party was marked by a "commitment to broad principles of personal liberty, social mobility, and westward expansion." Political scientist James A.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Influenced by the Jeffersonian belief in equality, by 1824 all but three states had removed property-owning requirements for voting.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Though open to some redistributive measures, Jefferson saw a strong centralized government as a threat to freedom.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Thus, the Democratic-Republicans opposed Federalist efforts to build a strong, centralized state, and resisted the establishment of a national bank, the build-up of the army and the navy, and passage of the Alien and Sedition Acts.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Jefferson was especially averse to a national debt, which he believed to be inherently dangerous and immoral.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] After the party took power in 1800, Jefferson became increasingly concerned about foreign intervention and more open to programs of economic development conducted by the federal government.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] In an effort to promote economic growth and the development of a diversified economy, Jefferson's Democratic-Republican successors would oversee the construction of numerous federally funded infrastructure projects and implement protective tariffs.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] While economic policies were the original catalyst to the partisan split between the Democratic-Republicans and the Federalists, foreign policy was also a major factor that divided the parties.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Most Americans supported the French Revolution prior to the Execution of Louis XVI in 1793, but Federalists began to fear the radical egalitarianism of the revolution as it became increasingly violent.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Jefferson and other Democratic-Republicans defended the French Revolution until Napoleon ascended to power.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Democratic-Republican foreign policy was marked by support for expansionism, as Jefferson championed the concept of an "Empire of Liberty" that centered on the acquisition and settlement of western territories.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Under Jefferson, Madison, and Monroe, the United States completed the Louisiana Purchase, acquired Spanish Florida, and reached a treaty with Britain providing for shared sovereignty over Oregon Country.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] In 1823, the Monroe administration promulgated the Monroe Doctrine, which reiterated the traditional U.S. policy of neutrality with regard to European wars and conflicts, but declared that the United States would not accept the recolonization of any country by its former European master.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] From the foundation of the party, slavery divided the Democratic-Republicans.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Many Southern Democratic-Republicans, especially from the Deep South, defended the institution.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Jefferson and many other Democratic-Republicans from Virginia held an ambivalent view on slavery; Jefferson believed it was an immoral institution, but he opposed the immediate emancipation of all slaves on social and economic grounds.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Instead, he favored gradual phasing out of the institution.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Meanwhile, Northern Democratic-Republicans often took stronger anti-slavery positions than their Federalist counterparts, supporting measures like the abolition of slavery in Washington.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] In 1807, with President Jefferson's support, Congress outlawed the international slave trade, doing so at the earliest possible date allowed by the Constitution.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] After the War of 1812, Southerners increasingly came to view slavery as a beneficial institution rather than an unfortunate economic necessity, further polarizing the party over the issue.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Anti-slavery Northern Democratic-Republicans held that slavery was incompatible with the equality and individual rights promised by the Declaration of Independence and the Constitution.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] They further held that slavery had been permitted under the Constitution only as a local and impermanent exception, and thus, slavery should not be allowed to spread outside of the original thirteen states.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The anti-slavery positions developed by Northern Democratic-Republicans would influence later anti-slavery parties, including the Free Soil Party and the Republican Party.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Madison and Jefferson formed the Democratic-Republican Party from a combination of former Anti-Federalists and supporters of the Constitution who were dissatisfied with the Washington administration's policies.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Nationwide, Democratic-Republicans were strongest in the South, and many of party's leaders were wealthy Southern slaveowners.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The Democratic-Republicans also attracted middle class Northerners, such as artisans, farmers, and lower-level merchants, who were eager to challenge the power of the local elite.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Every state had a distinct political geography that shaped party membership; in Pennsylvania, the Republicans were weakest around Philadelphia and strongest in Scots-Irish settlements in the west.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The Federalists had broad support in New England, but in other places they relied on wealthy merchants and landowners.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] After 1800, the Federalists collapsed in the South and West, though the party remained competitive in New England and in some Mid-Atlantic states.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Historian Sean Wilentz writes that, after assuming power in 1801, the Democratic-Republicans began to factionalize into three main groups: moderates, radicals, and Old Republicans.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The Old Republicans, led by John Randolph, were a loose group of influential Southern plantation owners who strongly favored states' rights and denounced any form of compromise with the Federalists.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The moderate faction consisted of many former supporters of the ratification of the Constitution, including James Madison, who were more accepting of Federalist economic programs and sought conciliation with moderate Federalists.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] After 1810, a younger group of nationalist Democratic-Republicans, led by Henry Clay and John C.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] These nationalists favored federally funded internal improvements and high tariffs, positions that would form the basis for Clay's American System.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] In addition to its base among the leaders of Clay and Calhoun's generation, nationalist policies also proved attractive to many older Democratic-Republicans, including James Monroe.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The Panic of 1819 sparked a backlash against nationalist policies, and many of those opposed to the nationalist policies rallied around William H.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Crawford until he had a major stroke in 1823.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] After the 1824 election, most of Crawford's followers, including Martin Van Buren, gravitated to Andrew Jackson, forming a major part of the coalition that propelled Jackson to victory in the 1828 election.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The Democratic-Republican Party invented campaign and organizational techniques that were later adopted by the Federalists and became standard American practice.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] It was especially effective in building a network of newspapers in major cities to broadcast its statements and editorialize its policies.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Fisher Ames, a leading Federalist, used the term "Jacobin" to link members of Jefferson's party to the radicals of the French Revolution.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] He blamed the newspapers for electing Jefferson and wrote they were "an overmatch for any Government....
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The Jacobins owe their triumph to the unceasing use of this engine; not so much to skill in use of it as by repetition".
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] As one historian explained: "It was the good fortune of the Republicans to have within their ranks a number of highly gifted political manipulators and propagandists.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Some of them had the ability... to not only see and analyze the problem at hand but to present it in a succinct fashion; in short, to fabricate the apt phrase, to coin the compelling slogan and appeal to the electorate on any given issue in language it could understand".
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Outstanding propagandists included editor William Duane (1760–1835) and party leaders Albert Gallatin, Thomas Cooper and Jefferson himself.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Just as important was effective party organization of the sort that John J.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] In 1796, he managed the Jefferson campaign in Pennsylvania, blanketing the state with agents who passed out 30,000 hand-written tickets, naming all 15 electors (printed tickets were not allowed).
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Beckley told one agent: "In a few days a select republican friend from the City will call upon you with a parcel of tickets to be distributed in your County.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Any assistance and advice you can furnish him with, as to suitable districts & characters, will I am sure be rendered".
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Beckley was the first American professional campaign manager and his techniques were quickly adopted in other states.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The emergence of the new organizational strategies can be seen in the politics of Connecticut around 1806, which have been well documented by Cunningham.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The Federalists dominated Connecticut, so the Republicans had to work harder to win.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] In 1806, the state leadership sent town leaders instructions for the forthcoming elections.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Every town manager was told by state leaders "to appoint a district manager in each district or section of his town, obtaining from each an assurance that he will faithfully do his duty".
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] These highly detailed returns were to be sent to the county manager and in turn were compiled and sent to the state manager.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Using these lists of potential voters, the managers were told to get all eligible people to town meetings and help the young men qualify to vote.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The state manager was responsible for supplying party newspapers to each town for distribution by town and district managers.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] This highly coordinated "get-out-the-vote" drive would be familiar to future political campaigners, but was the first of its kind in world history.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] After the 1824 presidential election the Democratic-Republicans split into factions.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The coalition of Jacksonians, Calhounites, and Crawfordites built by Andrew Jackson and Martin Van Buren coalesced into the Democratic Party, which dominated presidential politics in the decades prior to the Civil War.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Supporters of John Quincy Adams and Henry Clay would form the main opposition to Jackson as the National Republican Party, which in turn eventually formed part of the Whig Party, which was the second major party in the United States between the 1830s and the early 1850s.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The diverse and changing nature of the Democratic-Republican Party allowed both major parties to claim that they stood for Jeffersonian principles.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The Whig Party fell apart in the 1850s due to divisions over the expansion of slavery into new territories.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The modern Republican Party was formed in 1854 to oppose the expansion of slavery, and many former Whig Party leaders joined the newly formed anti-slavery party.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The Republican Party sought to combine Jefferson and Jackson's ideals of liberty and equality with Clay's program of using an active government to modernize the economy.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The Democratic-Republican Party inspired the name of its two direct descendants or offshoots: the National Republican Party (Whigs) and the Democratic party, as well as the later newly created Republican Party.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Fear of a large debt is a major legacy of this party.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Andrew Jackson believed the national debt was a "national curse" and he took special pride in paying off the entire national debt in 1835.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Politicians ever since have used the issue of a high national debt to denounce the other party for profligacy and a threat to fiscal soundness and the nation's future.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] In their second presidential run, Jefferson and Burr received the same number of electoral votes.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Jefferson was subsequently chosen as President by the House of Representatives.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] While commonly labeled as the Federalist candidate, Clinton technically ran as a Democratic-Republican and was not nominated by the Federalist party itself, the latter simply deciding not to field a candidate.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] This did not prevent endorsements from state Federalist parties (such as in Pennsylvania), but he received the endorsement from the New York state Democratic-Republicans as well.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Crawford and Albert Gallatin were nominated for president and vice-president by a group of 66 Congressmen that called itself the "Democratic members of Congress".
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Gallatin later withdrew from the contest.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Andrew Jackson, John Quincy Adams and Henry Clay ran as Republicans, although they were not nominated by any national body.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] While Jackson won a plurality in the electoral college and popular vote, he did not win the constitutionally required majority of electoral votes to be elected president.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The contest was thrown to the House of Representatives, where Adams won with Clay's support.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The affiliation of many Congressmen in the earliest years is an assignment by later historians.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] The parties were slowly coalescing groups; at first there were many independents.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/democratic-republican-party] Cunningham noted that only about a quarter of the House of Representatives up until 1794 voted with Madison as much as two-thirds of the time and another quarter against him two-thirds of the time, leaving almost half as fairly independent.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] An **election** is a group decision-making process whereby a portion or all of a population or group votes to choose an individual or multiple individuals to hold public office or other position of responsibility.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Elections have been the usual mechanism by which representative democracy has operated since the 17th century.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Elections may fill offices in the legislature, sometimes in the executive and judiciary, and for regional and local government, such as cities or towns.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] This process is also used in many other Standardized Associations, public businesses, and organizations, from clubs to voluntary association and corporations.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Electoral reform describes the process of introducing fair electoral systems where they are not in place, or improving the fairness or effectiveness of existing systems.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Psephology is the study of results and other statistics relating to elections (especially with a view to predicting future results).
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] The term *elect* means "to select or to nominate", so sometimes other forms of balloting such as referendums are referred to as elections, especially in the United States.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Elections were used as early in history as ancient Greece and ancient Rome, and throughout the Medieval period to select rulers such as the Holy Roman Emperor (see imperial election) and the pope (see papal election).
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] 750s – 770s CE) in early medieval Bengal was elected by a group of feudal chieftains.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Such elections were quite common in contemporary societies of the region.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] In the Chola Empire, around 920 CE, in Uthiramerur (in present-day Tamil Nadu), palm leaves were used for selecting the village committee members.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] The leaves, with candidate names written on them, were put inside a mud pot.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] To select the committee members, a young boy was asked to take out as many leaves as the number of positions available.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] This was known as the *Kudavolai* system.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Athenian democratic elections, where all citizens could hold public office, were not introduced for another 247 years, until the reforms of Cleisthenes.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Under the earlier Solonian Constitution (c.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] 574 BC), all Athenian citizens were eligible to vote in the popular assemblies, on matters of law and policy, and as jurors, but only the three highest classes of citizens could vote in elections.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Nor were the lowest of the four classes of Athenian citizens (as defined by the extent of their wealth and property, rather than by birth) eligible to hold public office, through the reforms of Solon.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] The Spartan election of the Ephors, therefore, also predates the reforms of Solon in Athens by approximately 180 years.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Questions of suffrage, especially suffrage for minority groups, have dominated the history of elections.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Males, the dominant cultural group in North America and Europe, often dominated the electorate and continue to do so in many countries.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Early elections in countries such as the United Kingdom and the United States were dominated by landed or ruling class males.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] By 1920 all Western European and North American democracies had universal adult male suffrage (except Switzerland) and many countries began to consider women's suffrage.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Despite legally mandated universal suffrage for adult males, political barriers were sometimes erected to prevent fair access to elections (see civil rights movement).
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Elections are held in a variety of political, organizational, and corporate settings.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Many countries hold elections to select people to serve in their governments, but other types of organizations hold elections as well.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] For example, many corporations hold elections among shareholders to select a board of directors, and these elections may be mandated by corporate law.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] In many places, an election to the government is usually a competition among people who have already won a primary election within a political party.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Elections within corporations and other organizations often use procedures and rules that are similar to those of governmental elections.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] The question of who may vote is a central issue in elections.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] The electorate does not generally include the entire population; for example, many countries prohibit those who are under the age of majority from voting.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] All jurisdictions require a minimum age for voting.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] In Australia, Aboriginal people were not given the right to vote until 1962 (see 1967 referendum entry) and in 2010 the federal government removed the rights of prisoners serving for three years or more to vote (a large proportion of whom were Aboriginal Australians).
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Suffrage is limited to citizens of the country to ensure equal voting rights ("One man, one vote").
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Persons with multiple citizenships voting in multiple countries would violate the equal representation in voting.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] In the European Union, one can vote in municipal elections if one lives in the municipality and is an EU citizen; the nationality of the country of residence is not required.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] In some countries, voting is required by law.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Eligible voters may be subject to punitive measures such as a fine for not casting a vote.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] In Western Australia, the penalty for a first time offender failing to vote is a $20.00 fine, which increases to $50.00 if the offender refused to vote prior.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Historically the size of eligible voters, the electorate, was small due to the size of groups or communities and to the limited number privileged to vote like aristocrats and men of a city (citizens).
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] With more people having bourgeois citizen rights outside of cities, expanding the term citizen, the electorates grew to numbers beyond the thousands.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] At the same time the Kingdom of Great Britain had in 1780 about 214,000 eligible voters, 3% of the whole population.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Naturalization can reshape the electorate of a country.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] A representative democracy requires a procedure to govern nomination for political office.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] In many cases, nomination for office is mediated through preselection processes in organized political parties.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Non-partisan systems tend to be different from partisan systems as concerns nominations.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] In a direct democracy, one type of non-partisan democracy, any eligible person can be nominated.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Although elections were used in ancient Athens, in Rome, and in the selection of popes and Holy Roman emperors, the origins of elections in the contemporary world lie in the gradual emergence of representative government in Europe and North America beginning in the 17th century.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] In some systems no nominations take place at all, with voters free to choose any person at the time of voting—with some possible exceptions such as through a minimum age requirement—in the jurisdiction.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] In a democracy, the members of the government are elected by a portion of the people who vote in an election.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Elections are a way for an electorate to *elect*, that is *choose*, from two or more different candidates.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Many countries in the world see elections fought principally between two opposing parties, known as a two-party system.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] These two will be the most established and most popular parties in the country.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] For example, in the US, the competition is between the Republicans and the Democrats.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Many other countries have multi-party systems where different socio-economic classes, ethnic and racial groups, regions and other diversities each have their own party.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] In an indirect or representative democracy, *voting* and elections are the method by which the people choose the people who will represent them, whilst making decisions.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Under Direct democracy the people vote to show their preferences to make policy decisions directly without selecting a representative to decide for them.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] A majority vote is when more than half of voters vote for the same person or party.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] This happens any time only two are in the running for a post but only sometimes when two or more candidates are in the running.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Plurality is when the successful candidate or candidates are decided just by relative strength, having more votes than the other candidates, whether in a multiple-winner context or in a single-winner context.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Many countries use a combination of factors to decide who has power, not the at-large "popular vote" using either the majority or plurality method.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Most influential of these factors are districts that divide the electorate.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Electoral systems consist of the detailed constitutional arrangements and voting systems that convert the vote into a political decision.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] The first step is for each voter to cast a ballot, which may be a simple single-choice ballot or another type such as multiple choice or a ranked ballot.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Then the votes (either taken at-large or in electoral districts) are tallied, for which various vote counting systems may be used.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] The voting system then allocates the seats on the basis of the tally.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Most systems allocate seats based on relative strength (pluralities), majorities, or proportional representation, or a a mixture of these systems.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Among the proportional systems, the most commonly used are party-list proportional representation (list PR).
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Among majority- or plurality-based systems the common systems include first-past-the-post electoral system (single winner plurality voting) and different methods of majority voting (such as the widely used two-round system).
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Mixed systems combine elements of both proportional and majoritarian/plurality systems, with some (mixed-member proportional) typically producing results closer to the former and others (e.g. parallel voting) sometimes having just as much dis-proportionality as first past the post.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Many countries have electoral reform movements that advocate for change to other election systems such as proportional representation, approval voting, single transferable vote, instant runoff voting or a Condorcet method.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] These alternative systems also are popular for lesser elections in some countries where more important elections still use more traditional counting methods.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] While openness and accountability are usually considered cornerstones of a democratic system, the act of casting a vote and the content of a voter's ballot are usually an important exception.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] The secret ballot is a relatively modern development, but it is now considered crucial in most free and fair elections, as it limits the effectiveness of intimidation.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Many electoral methods are used in the world.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] The purpose of an election may be to choose one person, such as a president, or a group of members, such as a committee or a parliament.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Different voting systems require different levels of support to be elected.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Plurality voting (First-past-the-post voting) elects the candidate with more votes than any other single candidate.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] It does not require the winner to achieve a majority, to have more than half of the total votes cast.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] In First-past-the-post voting, when more than two candidates run, the winner commonly has less than half of the vote, as few as 18 percent were recorded in 2014 in Toronto.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] In Instant-runoff voting, a candidate must have a majority of votes to be elected, although presence of exhausted votes may mean that the majority at time of final count is not majority of votes cast initially.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] In STV, any candidate who takes quota (usually set at much less than half of the votes) is elected; others without quota (but with more votes than any other single candidate) may be declared elected as well.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Side effects of First-past-the-post voting include a waste of votes due to vote splitting, a two-party system and political polarization due to electing candidates that do not support centrism.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] To understand why a race using First-past-the-post voting tends to favor less-centric candidates, consider a simple lab experiment where students in a class vote for their favorite marble.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] If five marbles are assigned names and are placed "up for election", and if three of them are green, one is red, and one is blue, then a green marble will rarely win the election.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] The reason for the green's lack of success is vote splitting.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] The three green marbles will split the votes of those who prefer green.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] In fact, in this analogy, the only way that a green marble is likely to win is if more than three-fifths of the voters prefer green.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] If the experiment is repeated with other colors, the color that is in the majority (if the majority is split among multiple choices) will still rarely win.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] In other words, from a purely mathematical perspective, a single-winner system tends to favor a winner that is different from the majority, if the majority runs multiple candidates, and if the minority group runs just one candidate.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] This minority rule success can also result if multiple winners are elected and voters cast multiple votes (Plurality block voting).
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] But even if the majority is split among multiple candidates, proportionate results can still be produced if votes can be transferred, as under STV, or if multiple winners are elected and each voter has just one vote.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Alternatives to first-past-the-post voting include approval voting, two-round, proportional representation, and instant-runoff voting.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] With approval voting, voters are encouraged to vote for as many candidates as they approve of, so the winner is much more likely to be any one of the five marbles because people who prefer green will be able to vote for every one of the green marbles.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] With two-round elections, the field of candidates is thinned prior to the second round of voting.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] In most cases, the winner must receive a majority of the votes, which is more than half.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] If no candidate obtains a majority in the first round, then the two candidates with the most significant plurality run again for the second round of voting.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Variants exist regarding these two points: the requirement for being elected at the first round is sometimes less than 50%, and the rules for participation in the runoff may vary.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] block voting are often used for at-large positions such as members of a city council.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] In a voting system that uses *multiple votes* (Plurality block voting), the voter can vote for a multiple-member subset of the running candidates.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] So, a voter might vote for Alice, Bob, and Charlie, rejecting Daniel and Emily.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Approval voting uses such multiple votes.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Instant-runoff voting and STV uses single ranked votes.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] In IRV, if no single candidate has 50% of the vote, then the candidate with the fewest votes is excluded and their votes are redistributed according to the voter's nominated order of preference.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] The process repeats itself until a candidate has 50% or more votes.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] The system is designed to produce the same result as an exhaustive ballot but using only a single round of voting.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Under STV, ranked voting is used in a proportional representation format.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] PR-STV is used in Australia, Ireland and Malta.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Voters rank candidates to indicate first preference and back-up preferences.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] In say a four-seat constituency, quota is 20 percent of the valid vote plus 1 (if Droop quota is used).
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Every candidate with quota (of 1st preferences alone or combination of first preferences and later preferences) will be elected.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] If a candidate has more than a quota and seats are yet to be filled, his/her surplus will be distributed to other candidates in proportion to the voter's preferences marked on the vote if any.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] In the Quota Borda System (QBS), the voters also cast their preferences, 1,2,3,4... as they wish.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] In the analysis, all 1st preferences are counted; all 2nd preferences are counted; after these preferences have been translated into points per the rules of a Modified Borda Count (MBC), the candidates' points are also counted.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Seats are awarded to any candidates with a quota of 1st preferences; to any pair of candidates with two quotas of 1st/2nd preferences; and if seats are still to be filled, to those candidates with the highest MBC scores.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] In a voting system that uses a *ranked vote*, the voter ranks the candidates in order of preference.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] For example, they might mark a preference for Bob in the first place, then Emily, then Alice, then Daniel, and finally Charlie.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Ranked voting systems, such as those used in Australia and Ireland, use a ranked vote.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] In a voting system that uses a *scored vote* (or *range vote*), the voter gives each alternative a number between one and ten (the upper and lower bounds may vary).
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Some "multiple-winner" systems such as the Single Non-Transferable Vote, SNTV, used in Afghanistan and Vanuatu, allow a voter to cast one vote even though multiple members are elected in the district.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] The Condorcet rule is used (sometimes) in decision-making.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] The voters or elected representatives cast their preferences on one, some, or all options, 1,2,3,4... as in PR-STV or QBS.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] In the analysis, option A is compared to option B, and if A is more popular than B, then A wins this pairing.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Next, A is compared with option C, then D, and so on.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] When elections are called, politicians and their supporters attempt to influence policy by competing directly for the votes of constituents in what are called campaigns.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Supporters for a campaign can be either formally organized or loosely affiliated, and frequently utilize campaign advertising.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] It is common for political scientists to attempt to predict elections via political forecasting methods.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] The most expensive election campaign included US$7 billion spent on the 2012 United States presidential election and is followed by the US$5 billion spent on the 2014 Indian general election.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] The nature of democracy is that elected officials are accountable to the people, and they must return to the voters at prescribed intervals to seek their mandate to continue in office.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] For that reason, most democratic constitutions provide that elections are held at fixed regular intervals.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] In the United States, elections for public offices are typically held between every two and six years in most states and at the federal level, with exceptions for elected judicial positions that may have longer terms of office.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] There is a variety of schedules, for example, presidents: the President of Ireland is elected every seven years, the President of Russia and the President of Finland every six years, the President of France every five years, President of the United States every four years.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Predetermined or fixed election dates have the advantage of fairness and predictability.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] They tend to greatly lengthen campaigns, and make dissolving the legislature (parliamentary system) more problematic if the date should happen to fall at a time when dissolution is inconvenient (e.g. when war breaks out).
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Other states (e.g., the United Kingdom) only set maximum time in office, and the executive decides exactly when within that limit it will actually go to the polls.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] In practice, this means the government remains in power for close to its full term, and chooses an election date it calculates to be in its best interests (unless something special happens, such as a motion of no-confidence).
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] This calculation depends on a number of variables, such as its performance in opinion polls and the size of its majority.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Postponing elections beyond the full term has been associated with democratic backsliding.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] In rolling elections, voters have information about previous voters' choices.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] While in the first elections, there may be plenty of hopeful candidates, in the last rounds consensus on one winner is generally achieved.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] In today's context of rapid communication, candidates can put disproportionate resources into competing strongly in the first few stages, because those stages affect the reaction of latter stages.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] In many of the countries with weak rule of law, the most common reason why elections do not meet international standards of being "free and fair" is interference from the incumbent government.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Dictators may use the powers of the executive (police, martial law, censorship, physical implementation of the election mechanism, etc.) to remain in power despite popular opinion in favour of removal.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Non-governmental entities can also interfere with elections, through physical force, verbal intimidation, or fraud, which can result in improper casting or counting of votes.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Monitoring for and minimizing electoral fraud is also an ongoing task in countries with strong traditions of free and fair elections.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Problems that prevent an election from being "free and fair" take various forms.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] The electorate may be poorly informed about issues or candidates due to lack of freedom of the press, lack of objectivity in the press due to state or corporate control, or lack of access to news and political media.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Freedom of speech may be curtailed by the state, favouring certain viewpoints or state propaganda.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Scheduling frequent elections can also lead to voter fatigue and political apathy.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Gerrymandering and wasted votes due to electoral thresholds can prevent all votes from counting equally.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Exclusion of opposition candidates from eligibility for office, needlessly high nomination rules on who may be a candidate, are some of the ways the structure of an election can be changed to favour a specific faction or candidate.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Those in power may arrest or assassinate candidates, suppress or even criminalize campaigning, close campaign headquarters, harass or beat campaign workers, or intimidate voters with violence.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Foreign electoral intervention can also occur, with the United States interfering between 1946 and 2000 in 81 elections and Russia or the Soviet Union in 36.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] In 2018 the most intense interventions, utilizing false information, were by China in Taiwan and by Russia in Latvia; the next highest levels were in Bahrain, Qatar and Hungary.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Other examples include persuading candidates not to run, such as through blackmailing, bribery, intimidation or physical violence.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] A **sham election**, or **show election** is an election that is held purely for show; that is, without any significant political choice or real impact on the results of the election.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Sham elections are a common event in dictatorships that feel the need to feign the appearance of public legitimacy.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Published results usually show high voter turnout and high support (typically at least 80%, and close to 100% in many cases) for the prescribed candidates or for the referendum choice that favours the political party in power.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Dictatorial regimes can also organize sham elections with results simulating those that might be achieved in democratic countries.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Sometimes, only one government-approved candidate is allowed to run in sham elections with no opposition candidates allowed, or opposition candidates are arrested on false charges (or even without any charges) before the election to prevent them from running.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Ballots may contain only one "yes" option, or in the case of a simple "yes or no" question, security forces often persecute people who pick "no", thus encouraging them to pick the "yes" option.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] In other cases, those who vote receive stamps in their passport for doing so, while those who did not vote (and thus do not receive stamps) are persecuted as enemies of the people.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Sham elections can sometimes backfire against the party in power, especially if the regime believes they are popular enough to win without coercion, fraud or suppressing the opposition.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] The most famous example of this was the 1990 Myanmar general election, in which the government-sponsored National Unity Party suffered a landslide defeat by the opposition National League for Democracy and consequently, the results were annulled.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Some scholars argue that the predominance of elections in modern liberal democracies masks the fact that they are actually aristocratic selection mechanisms that deny each citizen an equal chance of holding public office.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Such views were expressed as early as the time of Ancient Greece by Aristotle.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] These four factors result in the evaluation of candidates based on voters' partial standards of quality and social saliency (for example, skin colour and good looks).
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] This leads to self-selection biases in candidate pools due to unobjective standards of treatment by voters and the costs (barriers to entry) associated with raising one's political profile.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Ultimately, the result is the election of candidates who are superior (whether in actuality or as perceived within a cultural context) and objectively unlike the voters they are supposed to represent.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Evidence suggests that the concept of electing representatives was originally conceived to be different from democracy.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Prior to the 18th century, some societies in Western Europe used sortition as a means to select rulers, a method which allowed regular citizens to exercise power, in keeping with understandings of democracy at the time.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] The idea of what constituted a legitimate government shifted in the 18th century to include consent, especially with the rise of the enlightenment.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] From this point onward, sortition fell out of favor as a mechanism for selecting rulers.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] On the other hand, elections began to be seen as a way for the masses to express popular consent repeatedly, resulting in the triumph of the electoral process until the present day.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] This conceptual misunderstanding of elections as open and egalitarian when they are not innately so may thus be a root cause of the problems in contemporary governance.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Those in favor of this view argue that the modern system of elections was never meant to give ordinary citizens the chance to exercise power - merely privileging their right to consent to those who rule.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] Therefore, the representatives that modern electoral systems select for are too disconnected, unresponsive, and elite-serving.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] To deal with this issue, various scholars have proposed alternative models of democracy, many of which include a return to sortition-based selection mechanisms.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/election] The extent to which sortition should be the dominant mode of selecting rulers or instead be hybridised with electoral representation remains a topic of debate.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The **Federalist Party** was a conservative and nationalist American political party and the first known political party in the United States.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] It dominated the national government under the leadership of Alexander Hamilton from 1789 to 1801.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The party was defeated by the Democratic-Republican Party in 1800, and it became a minority party while keeping its stronghold in New England.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] It made a brief resurgence by opposing the War of 1812, then collapsed with its last presidential candidate in 1816, although it lasted for a few years afterwards.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The party appealed to businesses who favored banks, national over state government, and maintaining an army and navy.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] In world affairs, the party preferred Great Britain and strongly opposed involvement in the French Revolutionary and Napoleonic Wars.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The party favored centralization, federalism, modernization, industrialization, and protectionism.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The Federalists called for a strong national government that promoted economic growth and fostered friendly relationships with Great Britain in opposition to Revolutionary France.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The Federalist Party came into being between 1789 and 1790 as a national coalition of bankers and businessmen in support of Hamilton's fiscal policies.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] These supporters worked in every state to build an organized party committed to a fiscally sound and nationalistic government.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The only Federalist president was John Adams.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] George Washington was broadly sympathetic to the Federalist program, but he remained officially non-partisan during his entire presidency.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The Federalist Party controlled the national government until 1801, when it was overwhelmed by the Democratic-Republican opposition led by President Thomas Jefferson.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Federalist policies called for a national bank, tariffs, and good relations with Great Britain as expressed in the Jay Treaty negotiated in 1794.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Hamilton developed the concept of implied powers and successfully argued the adoption of that interpretation of the Constitution.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The Democratic-Republicans led by Jefferson denounced most of the Federalist policies, especially the bank and implied powers, and vehemently attacked the Jay Treaty as a sell-out of American interests to Britain.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The Jay Treaty passed and the Federalists won most of the major legislative battles in the 1790s.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] They held a strong base in the nation's cities and in New England.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] They factionalized when President Adams secured peace with France, to the anger of Hamilton's larger faction.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The Jeffersonians won the presidential election of 1800, and the Federalists never returned to power.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] They recovered some strength through their intense opposition to the War of 1812, but they practically vanished during the Era of Good Feelings that followed the end of the war in 1815.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The Federalists left a lasting legacy in the form of a strong federal government.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] After losing executive power, they decisively shaped Supreme Court policy for another three decades through Chief Justice John Marshall.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The term "Federalist" was previously used to refer to a somewhat different coalition of nationalists led by Washington, which advocated replacing the weaker national government under the Articles of Confederation with a new Constitution in 1789.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] This early coalition included Hamilton and James Madison.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The Federalists of this time were rivaled by the Anti-Federalists, who opposed the ratification of the Constitution and objected to creating a stronger central government.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The critiques of the Constitution raised by the Anti-Federalists influenced the creation of the Bill of Rights.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Federalists responded to these objections by promising to add a bill of rights as amendments to the Constitution to satisfy these concerns, which aided in securing acceptance and ratification of the Constitution by the states.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The new United States Congress, initially with a Federalist majority, submitted to the states a series of amendments to guarantee specific freedoms and rights; once ratified, these would become the first ten amendments to the Constitution.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Upon taking office in 1789, President Washington nominated his wartime chief of staff Alexander Hamilton to the new office of Secretary of the Treasury.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Hamilton wanted a strong national government with financial credibility, and he proposed the ambitious Hamiltonian economic program that involved the assumption of the state debts incurred during the American Revolution.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] This created a national debt and the means to pay it off, and it set up a national bank along with tariffs, with James Madison playing major roles in the program.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Parties were considered to be divisive and harmful to republicanism, and no similar parties existed anywhere in the world.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] By 1789, Hamilton started building a nationwide coalition (a "Pro-Administration" faction), realizing the need for vocal political support in the states.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] He formed connections with like-minded nationalists and used his network of treasury agents to link together friends of the government, especially merchants and bankers, in the new nation's dozen major cities.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] His attempts to manage politics in the national capital to get his plans through Congress brought strong responses across the country.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] In the process, what began as a capital faction soon assumed status as a national faction and then as the new Federalist Party.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The Federalist Party supported Hamilton's vision of a strong centralized government and agreed with his proposals for a national bank and heavy government subsidies.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] In foreign affairs, they supported neutrality in the war between France and Great Britain.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Hamilton proposed to fund the national and state debts, and Madison and John J.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Beckley began organizing a party to oppose it.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] This "Anti-Administration" faction became what is now called the Democratic-Republican Party, led by Madison and Thomas Jefferson.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] This party attracted many Anti-Federalists who were wary of a centralized government.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] By the early 1790s, newspapers started calling Hamilton supporters "Federalists" and their opponents "Republicans", "Jeffersonians", or "Democratic-Republicans".
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Jefferson's supporters usually called themselves "Republicans" and their party the "Republican Party".
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The Federalist Party became popular with businessmen and New Englanders, and Republicans were mostly farmers who opposed a strong central government.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Cities were usually Federalist strongholds, whereas frontier regions were heavily Republican.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The Congregationalists of New England and the Episcopalians in the larger cities supported the Federalists, while other minority denominations tended toward the Republican camp.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Urban Catholics were generally Federalists.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The state networks of both parties began to operate in 1794 or 1795, and patronage became a factor.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The winner-takes-all election system opened a wide gap between winners, who got all the patronage, and losers who got none.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Hamilton had many lucrative Treasury jobs to dispense—there were 1,700 of them by 1801.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Jefferson had one part-time job in the State Department, which he gave to journalist Philip Freneau to attack the Federalists.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] In New York, George Clinton won the election for governor and used the vast state patronage fund to help the Republican cause.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Washington tried and failed to moderate the feud between his two top cabinet members.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] He was re-elected without opposition in 1792.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The Democratic-Republicans (as they were now known) nominated New York's Governor Clinton to replace Federalist John Adams as vice president, but Adams won.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The balance of power in Congress was close, with some members still undecided between the parties.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] In early 1793, Jefferson secretly prepared resolutions introduced by Virginia Congressman William Branch Giles designed to repudiate Hamilton and weaken the Washington Administration.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Hamilton defended his administration of the nation's complicated financial affairs, which none of his critics could decipher until the arrival in Congress of Republican Albert Gallatin in 1793.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The French Revolution and the subsequent war between royalist Britain and republican France decisively shaped American politics in 1793–1800 and threatened to entangle the country in wars that "mortally threatened its very existence".
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The French revolutionaries guillotined King Louis XVI in January 1793, and subsequently declared war on Britain.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The French king had been decisive in helping the United States achieve independence, but now he was dead and many of the pro-American aristocrats in France were exiled or executed.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Federalists warned that American republicans threatened to replicate the horrors of the French Revolution and successfully mobilized most conservatives and many clergymen.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The Republicans, some of whom had been strong Francophiles, responded with support even through the Reign of Terror, when thousands were guillotined, though it was at this point that many began backing away from their pro-France leanings.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Many of those executed had been friends of the United States, such as the Comte D'Estaing, whose fleet had fought alongside the Americans in the Revolution (Lafayette had already fled into exile, and Thomas Paine went to prison in France).
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The republicans denounced Hamilton, Adams and even Washington as friends of Britain, as secret monarchists, aristocrats and as enemies of the republican values.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The level of rhetoric reached a fever pitch.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] In 1793, Paris sent a new minister, Edmond-Charles Genêt (known as *Citizen Genêt*), who systematically mobilized pro-French sentiment and encouraged Americans to support France's war against Britain and Spain.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Genêt funded local Democratic-Republican Societies that attacked Federalists.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] He hoped for a favorable new treaty and for repayment of the debts owed to France.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Acting aggressively, Genêt outfitted privateers that sailed with American crews under a French flag and attacked British shipping.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] He tried to organize expeditions of Americans to invade Spanish Louisiana and Spanish Florida.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] When Secretary of State Jefferson told Genêt he was pushing American friendship past the limit, Genêt threatened to go over the government's head and rouse public opinion on behalf of France.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Even Jefferson agreed this was blatant foreign interference in domestic politics.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Genêt's extremism seriously embarrassed the Jeffersonians and cooled popular support for promoting the French Revolution and getting involved in its wars.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Recalled to Paris for execution, Genêt kept his head and instead went to New York, where he became a citizen and married the daughter of Governor Clinton.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Jefferson left office, ending the coalition cabinet and allowing the Federalists to dominate.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The Jay Treaty battle in 1794–1795 was the effort by Washington, Hamilton and John Jay to resolve numerous difficulties with Britain.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Some of these issues dated to the Revolution, such as boundaries, debts owed in each direction and the continued presence of British forts in the Northwest Territory.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] In addition, the United States hoped to open markets in the British Caribbean and end disputes stemming from the naval war between Britain and France.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Most of all the goal was to avert a war with Britain—a war opposed by the Federalists, that some historians claim the Jeffersonians wanted.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] As a neutral party, the United States argued it had the right to carry goods anywhere it wanted.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The British nevertheless seized American ships carrying goods from the French West Indies.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The Federalists favored Britain in the war and by far most of America's foreign trade was with Britain; hence a new treaty was called for.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] One possible alternative was war with Britain, a war that the United States was ill-prepared to fight.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The Republicans wanted to pressure Britain to the brink of war (and assumed that the United States could defeat a weak Britain).
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Republicans protested against the treaty and organized their supporters.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The Federalists realized they had to mobilize their popular vote, so they mobilized their newspapers, held rallies, counted votes and especially relied on the prestige of President Washington.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The contest over the Jay Treaty marked the first flowering of grassroots political activism in the United States, directed and coordinated by two national parties.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Politics was no longer the domain of politicians as every voter was called on to participate.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The new strategy of appealing directly to the public worked for the Federalists as public opinion shifted to support the Jay Treaty.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The Federalists controlled the Senate and they ratified it by exactly the necessary two-thirds vote vote (20–10) in 1795.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] However, the Republicans did not give up and public opinion swung toward the Republicans after the Treaty fight and in the South the Federalists lost most of the support they had among planters.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The excise tax of 1791 caused grumbling from the frontier including threats of tax resistance.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Corn, the chief crop on the frontier, was too bulky to ship over the mountains to market unless it was first distilled into whiskey.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] This was profitable as the United States population consumed per capita relatively large quantities of liquor.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] After the excise tax, the backwoodsmen complained the tax fell on them rather than on the consumers.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Cash poor, they were outraged that they had been singled out to pay off the "financiers and speculators" back in the East and to pay the salaries of the federal revenue officers who began to swarm the hills looking for illegal stills.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Insurgents in western Pennsylvania shut the courts and hounded federal officials, but Jeffersonian leader Albert Gallatin mobilized the western moderates and thus forestalled a serious outbreak.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Washington, seeing the need to assert federal supremacy, called out 13,000 state militia and marched toward Washington, Pennsylvania to suppress this Whiskey Rebellion.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The rebellion evaporated in late 1794 as Washington approached, personally leading the army (only two sitting Presidents have directly led American military forces, the other being Madison in an attempt to save the White House during the War of 1812).
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The rebels dispersed and there was no fighting.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Federalists were relieved that the new government proved capable of overcoming rebellion while Republicans, with Gallatin as their new hero, argued there never was a real rebellion and the whole episode was manipulated in order to accustom Americans to a standing army.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Angry petitions flowed in from three dozen Democratic-Republican Societies created by Citizen Genêt.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Washington attacked the societies as illegitimate, and many disbanded.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Federalists now ridiculed Republicans as "democrats" (meaning in favor of mob rule) or "Jacobins" (a reference to the Reign of Terror in France).
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Washington refused to run for a third term, establishing a two-term precedent that was to stand until 1940 and eventually to be enshrined in the Constitution as the 22nd Amendment.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Washington never considered himself a member of any party, but broadly supported most Federalist policies.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Hamilton distrusted Vice President Adams—who felt the same way about Hamilton—but was unable to block his claims to the succession.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The election of 1796 was the first partisan affair in the nation's history and one of the more scurrilous in terms of newspaper attacks.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Adams swept New England and Jefferson the South, with the middle states leaning to Adams.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Adams was the winner by a margin of three electoral votes and Jefferson, as the runner-up, became vice president under the system set out in the Constitution prior to the ratification of the 12th Amendment.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Adams became president in 1797, when the Federalists controlled both houses of Congress, the presidency, eight state legislatures and ten governorships.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Foreign affairs continued to be the central concern of American politics, for the war raging in Europe threatened to drag in the United States.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Historian Sarah Kreps in 2018 argues the Federalist faction led by President Adams during the 1798 Quasi-War could correspond to "today's right-of-center party".
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The new president was a loner, who made decisions without consulting Hamilton or other "High Federalists".
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Benjamin Franklin once quipped that Adams was a man who was always honest, often brilliant and sometimes mad.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Adams was popular among the Federalist rank and file, but had neglected to build state or local political bases of his own and neglected to take control of his own cabinet.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] As a result, his cabinet answered more to Hamilton than to himself.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Hamilton was especially popular because he rebuilt the Army—and had commissions to give out.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] After an American delegation was insulted in Paris in the XYZ affair of 1797, public opinion ran strongly against the French.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] An undeclared "Quasi-War" with France from 1798 to 1800 saw each side attacking and capturing the other's shipping.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] It was called "quasi" because there was no declaration of war, but escalation was a serious threat.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] At the peak of their popularity, the Federalists took advantage by preparing for an invasion by the French Army.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] To silence Administration critics, the Federalists passed the Alien and Sedition Acts in 1798.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The Alien Act empowered the President to deport such aliens as he declared to be dangerous.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The Sedition Act made it a crime to print false, scandalous and malicious criticisms of the federal government, but it conspicuously failed to criminalize criticism of Vice President Thomas Jefferson.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Several Republican newspaper editors were convicted under the Act and fined or jailed and three Democratic-Republican newspapers were shut down.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] In response, Jefferson and Madison secretly wrote the Kentucky and Virginia Resolutions passed by the two states' legislatures that declared the Alien and Sedition Acts unconstitutional and insisted the states had the power to nullify federal laws.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Undaunted, the Federalists created a navy, with new frigates; and a large new army, with Washington in nominal command and Hamilton in actual command.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] To pay for it all, they raised taxes on land, houses and slaves, leading to serious unrest.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] In one part of Pennsylvania, the John Fries's Rebellion broke out, with people refusing to pay the new taxes.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] John Fries was sentenced to death for treason, but received a pardon from Adams.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] In the elections of 1798, the Federalists did very well, but this issue started hurting the Federalists in 1799.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Early in 1799, Adams decided to free himself from Hamilton's overbearing influence, stunning the country and throwing his party into disarray by announcing a new peace mission to France.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The mission eventually succeeded, the "Quasi-War" ended and the new army was largely disbanded.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Hamiltonians called Adams a failure while Adams fired Hamilton's supporters still in the cabinet.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Hamilton and Adams intensely disliked one another, and the Federalists split between supporters of Hamilton ("High Federalists") and supporters of Adams.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Hamilton became embittered over his loss of political influence and wrote a scathing criticism of Adams' performance as president in an effort to throw Federalist support to Charles Cotesworth Pinckney.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Inadvertently, this split the Federalists and helped give the victory to Jefferson.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Adams's peace moves proved popular with the Federalist rank and file and he seemed to stand a good chance of re-election in 1800.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] If the Three-Fifths Compromise had not been enacted, he most likely would have won reelection since many Federalist legislatures removed the right to select electors from their constituents in fear of a Democratic victory.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Jefferson was again the opponent and Federalists pulled out all stops in warning that he was a dangerous revolutionary, hostile to religion, who would weaken the government, damage the economy and get into war with Britain.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Many believed that if Jefferson won the election, it would be the end of the newly formed United States.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The Republicans crusaded against the Alien and Sedition laws as well as the new taxes and proved highly effective in mobilizing popular discontent.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The election hinged on New York as its electors were selected by the legislature and given the balance of North and South, they would decide the presidential election.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Aaron Burr brilliantly organized his forces in New York City in the spring elections for the state legislature.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] By a few hundred votes, he carried the city—and thus the state legislature—and guaranteed the election of a Republican president.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] As a reward, he was selected by the Republican caucus in Congress as their vice-presidential candidate.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Alexander Hamilton, knowing the election was lost anyway, went public with a sharp attack on Adams that further divided and weakened the Federalists.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Members of the Republican Party planned to vote evenly for Jefferson and Burr because they did not want for it to seem as if their party was divided.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The party took the meaning literally and Jefferson and Burr tied in the election with 73 electoral votes.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] This sent the election to the House of Representatives to break the tie.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The Federalists had enough weight in the House to swing the election in either direction.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Many would rather have seen Burr in the office over Jefferson, but Hamilton, who had a strong dislike of Burr, threw his political weight behind Jefferson.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] During the election, neither Jefferson nor Burr attempted to swing the election in the House of Representatives.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Jefferson remained at Monticello to oversee the laying of bricks to a section of his home.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Jefferson allowed for his political beliefs and other ideologies to filter out through letters to his contacts.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Thanks to Hamilton's support, Jefferson would win the election and Burr would become his vice president.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The 1800 election marked the first time power had been transferred between opposing political parties, an act that occurred remarkably without bloodshed.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Though there had been strong words and disagreements, contrary to the Federalists fears, there was no war and no ending of one-government system to let in a new one.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] His patronage policy was to let the Federalists disappear through attrition.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Those Federalists such as John Quincy Adams (John Adams' own son) and Rufus King willing to work with him were rewarded with senior diplomatic posts, but there was no punishment of the opposition.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Jefferson had a very successful first term, typified by the Louisiana Purchase, which was supported by Hamilton, but opposed by most Federalists at the time as unconstitutional.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] However, Hamilton's influence cost Burr the governorship of New York, a key in the Essex Junto's plan, just as Hamilton's influence had cost Burr the presidency nearly four years before.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Hamilton's thwarting of Aaron Burr's ambitions for the second time was too much for Burr to bear.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Hamilton had known of the Essex Junto (whom Hamilton now regarded as apostate Federalists) and Burr's plans and opposed them vehemently.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] This opposition by Hamilton would lead to his fatal duel with Burr in July 1804.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The thoroughly disorganized Federalists hardly offered any opposition to Jefferson's reelection in 1804 and Federalists seemed doomed.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Jefferson had taken away most of their patronage, including federal judgeships.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The party now controlled only five state legislatures and seven governorships.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] After again losing the presidency in 1804, the party was now down to three legislatures and five governorships (four in New England).
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Their majorities in Congress were long gone, dropping in the Senate from 23 in 1796, and 21 in 1800 to only six in 1804.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] In New England and in some districts in the middle states, the Federalists clung to power, but the tendency from 1800 to 1812 was steady slippage almost everywhere as the Republicans perfected their organization and the Federalists tried to play catch-up.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Some younger leaders tried to emulate the Democratic-Republican tactics, but their overall disdain of democracy along with the upper class bias of the party leadership eroded public support.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] In the South, the Federalists steadily lost ground everywhere.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The Federalists continued for several years to be a major political party in New England and the Northeast, but never regained control of the presidency or the Congress.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] With the death of Washington and Hamilton and the retirement of Adams, the Federalists were left without a strong leader as Chief Justice John Marshall stayed out of politics.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] However, a few younger leaders did appear, notably Daniel Webster.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Federalist policies favored factories, banking and trade over agriculture and therefore became unpopular in the growing Western states.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] They were increasingly seen as aristocratic and unsympathetic to democracy.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] In the South, the party had lingering support in Maryland, but elsewhere was crippled by 1800 and faded away by 1808.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Massachusetts and Connecticut remained the party strongholds.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] After 1800, the major Federalist role came in the judiciary.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Although Jefferson managed to repeal the Judiciary Act of 1801 and thus dismissed many lower-level Federalist federal judges, the effort to impeach Supreme Court Justice Samuel Chase in 1804 failed.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Led by the last great Federalist, John Marshall as Chief Justice from 1801 to 1835, the Supreme Court carved out a unique and powerful role as the protector of the Constitution and promoter of nationalism.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] As the wars in Europe intensified, the United States became increasingly involved.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The Federalists restored some of their strength by leading the anti-war opposition to Jefferson and Madison between 1807 and 1814.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] President Jefferson imposed an embargo on Britain in 1807 as the Embargo Act of 1807 prevented all American ships from sailing to a foreign port.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The idea was that the British were so dependent on American supplies that they would come to terms.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] For 15 months, the Embargo wrecked American export businesses, largely based in the Boston-New York region, causing a sharp depression in the Northeast.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Evasion was common and Jefferson and Treasury Secretary Gallatin responded with tightened police controls more severe than anything the Federalists had ever proposed.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Public opinion was highly negative and a surge of support breathed fresh life into the Federalist Party.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] As Jefferson refrained from seeking a third term, the Republicans nominated Madison for the presidency in 1808.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Madison lost New England excluding Vermont, but swept the rest of the country and carried a Republican Congress.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Madison dropped the Embargo, opened up trade again and offered a carrot and stick approach.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] If either France or Britain agreed to stop their violations of American neutrality, the United States would cut off trade with the other country.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Tricked by French Emperor Napoleon into believing France had acceded to his demands, Madison turned his wrath on Britain and the War of 1812 began.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Young Daniel Webster, running for Congress from New Hampshire in 1812, first gained overnight fame with his anti-war speeches.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The nation was at war during the 1812 presidential election and war was the burning issue.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Opposition to the war was strong in traditional Federalist strongholds in New England and New York, where the party made a comeback in the elections of 1812 and 1814.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] In their second national convention in 1812, the Federalists, now the peace party, nominated DeWitt Clinton, the dissident Republican Mayor of New York City and an articulate opponent of the war, who had followed his uncle George Clinton as the leader of the Clintonian faction after his death.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Madison ran for reelection promising a relentless war against Britain and an honorable peace.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Clinton, denouncing Madison's weak leadership and incompetent preparations for war, could count on New England and New York.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] To win, he needed the middle states and there the campaign was fought out.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Those states were competitive and had the best-developed local parties and most elaborate campaign techniques, including nominating conventions and formal party platforms.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The Tammany Society in New York City highly favored Madison and the Federalists finally adopted the club idea in 1808.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Their Washington Benevolent Societies were semi-secret membership organizations which played a critical role in every northern state as they held meetings and rallies and mobilized Federalist votes.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] New Jersey went for Clinton, but Madison carried Pennsylvania and thus was reelected with 59% of the electoral votes.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] However, the Federalists gained 14 seats in Congress.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The War of 1812 went poorly for the Americans for two years.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Even though Britain was concentrating its military efforts on its war with Napoleon, the United States still failed to make any headway on land and was effectively blockaded at sea by the Royal Navy.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The British raided and burned Washington, D.C. in 1814 and sent a force to capture New Orleans.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The war was especially unpopular in New England.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The New England economy was highly dependent on trade and the British blockade threatened to destroy it entirely.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] In 1814, the British Navy finally managed to enforce their blockade on the New England coast, so the Federalists of New England sent delegates to the Hartford Convention in December 1814.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] During the proceedings of the Hartford Convention, secession from the Union was discussed, though the resulting report listed a set of grievances against the Democratic-Republican federal government and proposed a set of Constitutional amendments to address these grievances.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] They demanded financial assistance from Washington to compensate for lost trade and proposed constitutional amendments requiring a two-thirds vote in Congress before an embargo could be imposed, new states admitted, or war declared.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] It also indicated that if these proposals were ignored, then another convention should be called and given "such powers and instructions as the exigency of a crisis may require".
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The Federalist Massachusetts Governor had already secretly sent word to England to broker a separate peace accord.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Three Massachusetts "ambassadors" were sent to Washington to negotiate on the basis of this report.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] By the time the Federalist "ambassadors" got to Washington, the war was over and news of Andrew Jackson's stunning victory in the Battle of New Orleans had raised American morale immensely.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The "ambassadors" hastened back to Massachusetts, but not before they had done fatal damage to the Federalist Party.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The Federalists were thereafter associated with the disloyalty and parochialism of the Hartford Convention and destroyed as a political force.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Across the nation, Republicans used the great victory at New Orleans to ridicule the Federalists as cowards, defeatists and secessionists.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Pamphlets, songs, newspaper editorials, speeches and entire plays on the Battle of New Orleans drove home the point.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The Federalists fielded their last presidential candidate, Rufus King in 1816.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] With the party's passing, partisan hatreds and newspaper feuds declined and the nation entered the "Era of Good Feelings".
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Federalism in states like Massachusetts gradually blended into the conservative wing of the Democratic-Republicans.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] In the 1824 presidential election, New Englanders from both parties supported Adams, a native of the region.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] However, a few old Federalist leaders, who never forgave Adams for abandoning them, formed a ticket of unpledged electors with radical Democratic-Republicans.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] This ticket was overwhelmingly defeated and likely would have voted for Crawford.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Following 1824, no Federalist ran for governor of any state and most left for the National Republicans.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] After the dissolution of the final Federalist congressional caucus in 1825, the last traces of Federalist activity came in Delaware and Massachusetts local politics in the late 1820s.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] In other states there still technically existed Federalists (for example James Buchanan) but they were engaged in patronage with either Jackson or Adams.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] In Massachusetts, the Federalist Party ceased to function as a state organization in 1825, surviving only as a local Boston group for the next three years.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] In Delaware, the Federalist Party lasted until 1826 and controlled the Delaware House of Representatives.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] When Daniel Webster, representative of Boston, resigned in 1827 to run for U.S.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Senator, a caucus of Federalists met in Boston to nominate his replacement.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] A young William Lloyd Garrison persuaded the caucus to choose the Federalist Harrison Gray Otis, who ultimately declined.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The caucus then nominated the Anti-Jacksonian Benjamin Gorham, their original choice.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] In the 1828 presidential election, the Federalists were used as a scapegoat in Boston.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The Democratic Boston *Statesman* accused Adams of being a secret Hartford Federalist attempting to revive the "reign of terror" under his father.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] Adams responded by accusing the old Hartford Federalists of treason and attempting to dissolve the union to form their own confederation.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] The *Jackson Republican*, an ally of the Statesman and founded by former Federalist Theodore Lyman II, implicated Webster among the old Federalists Adams intended to impugn, leading to a libel suit.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] As a protest against Adams, several "Federal young men" who had been supporting Adams nominated a Federalist ticket of presidential electors.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] This ticket, headed by Otis and William Prescott Jr. and including three other members of the Hartford Convention, garnered a pitiful 156 votes in Boston and none elsewhere in the state.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] As with the previous election, Adams swept the city and state.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p01] That ticket, according to the best of knowledge of Samuel Eliot Morison, was "the last ticket ever voted for that bore the name of the once powerful party of Washington and Hamilton".
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] Fisher Ames (1758–1808) of Massachusetts ranks as one of the more influential figures of his era.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] Ames led Federalist ranks in the House of Representatives.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] His acceptance of the Bill of Rights garnered support in Massachusetts for the new Constitution.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] His greatest fame came as an orator who defined the principles of the Federalist Party and the follies of the Republicans.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] Ames offered one of the first great speeches in American Congressional history when he spoke in favor of the Jay Treaty.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] Ames was part of Hamilton's faction and cautioned against the excesses of democracy unfettered by morals and reason: "Popular reason does not always know how to act right, nor does it always act right when it knows".
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] He warned his countrymen of the dangers of flattering demagogues, who incite dis-union and lead their country into bondage: "Our country is too big for union, too sordid for patriotism, too democratic for liberty.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] What is to become of it, He who made it best knows.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] Its vice will govern it, by practising upon its folly.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] Intellectually, Federalists were profoundly devoted to liberty.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] As Samuel Eliot Morison explained, they believed that liberty is inseparable from union, that men are essentially unequal, that *vox populi* ("voice of the people") is seldom if ever *vox Dei* ("the voice of God") and that sinister outside influences are busy undermining American integrity.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] In terms of "classical conservatism", the Federalists did not support European-style aristocracy, monarchy, or established religion.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] Diggins says: "Thanks to the framers, American conservatism began on a genuinely lofty plane.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] James Madison, Alexander Hamilton, John Marshall, John Jay, James Wilson, and, above all, John Adams aspired to create a republic in which the values so precious to conservatives might flourish: harmony, stability, virtue, reverence, veneration, loyalty, self-discipline, and moderation.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] This was classical conservatism in its most authentic expression".
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] Federalists led the successful battles to abolish the international slave trade in New York City and the battle to abolish slavery in the state of New York.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] The Federalists' approach to nationalism was coined "open" nationalism in that it creates space for minority groups to have a voice in government.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] Many Federalists also created space for women to have a significant political role, which was not evident on the Democratic-Republican side.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] The Federalists were dominated by businessmen and merchants in the major cities who supported a strong national government.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] The party was closely linked to the modernizing, urbanizing, financial policies of Alexander Hamilton.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] These policies included the funding of the national debt and also assumption of state debts incurred during the Revolutionary War, the incorporation of a national Bank of the United States, the support of manufactures and industrial development, and the use of a tariff to fund the Treasury.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] While it has long been accepted that commercial groups are in support of the Federalists and agrarian groups are in support of the Democratic-Republicans, recent studies have shown that support for Federalists was also evident in agrarian groups.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] In foreign affairs, the Federalists opposed the French Revolution, engaged in the "Quasi War" (an undeclared naval war) with France in 1798–99, sought good relations with Britain and sought a strong army and navy.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] Ideologically, the controversy between Democratic-Republicans and Federalists stemmed from a difference of principle and style.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] In terms of style, the Federalists feared mob rule, thought an educated elite should represent the general populace in national governance and favored national power over state power.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] Democratic-Republicans distrusted Britain, bankers, merchants and did not want a powerful national government.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] The Federalists, notably Hamilton, were distrustful of "the people", the French and the Republicans.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] In the end, the nation synthesized the two positions, adopting representative democracy and a strong nation state.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] Just as importantly, American politics by the 1820s accepted the two-party system whereby rival parties stake their claims before the electorate and the winner takes control of majority in state legislatures and the Congress and gains governorships and the presidency.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] As time went on, the Federalists lost appeal with the average voter and were generally not equal to the tasks of party organization; hence they grew steadily weaker as the political triumphs of the Democratic-Republican Party grew.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] Madison's War", as they called it, the Federalists made a temporary comeback.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] However, they lost all their gains and more during the patriotic euphoria that followed the war.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] The membership was aging rapidly, but a few young men from New England did join the cause, most notably Daniel Webster.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] After 1816, the Federalists had no national power base apart from John Marshall's Supreme Court.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] They had some local support in New England, New York, eastern Pennsylvania, Maryland and Delaware.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] By then, nearly all remaining Federalists joined the Whigs.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] However, some former Federalists like James Buchanan, Louis McLane and Roger B.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] The "Old Republicans", led by John Randolph of Roanoke, refused to form a coalition with the Federalists and instead set up a separate opposition since Jefferson, Madison, Gallatin, Monroe, John C.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] All these measures were opposed to the strict construction of the Constitution, which was the formal basis of the Democratic-Republicans, but the drift of the party to support them could not be checked.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] It was aided by the Supreme Court, whose influence under John Marshall as a nationalizing factor now first became apparent.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] The whole change reconciled the Federalists to their absorption into the Democratic-Republican Party.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] Indeed, they claimed, with considerable show of justice, that the absorption was in the other direction: that the Democratic-Republicans had recanted and that the "Washington-Monroe policy", as they termed it after 1820, was all that Federalists had ever desired.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] The name "Federalist" came increasingly to be used in political rhetoric as a term of abuse and was denied by the Whigs, who pointed out that their leader Henry Clay was the Democratic-Republican Party leader in Congress during the 1810s.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] The Federalists had a weak base in the South, with their main base in the Northeast and especially New England, although there were some prominent southern Federalists like Charles Cotesworth Pinckney, who had been supported by Hamilton in the presidential election of 1800.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] In New England, the Federalist Party was closely linked to the Congregational church.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] When the party collapsed, the church was disestablished.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] In 1800 and other elections, the Federalists targeted infidelity in any form.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] They repeatedly charged that Republican candidates were atheistic or anti-religious, especially Jefferson, Paine, and Franklin.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] Conversely, the Baptists, Methodists, and other dissenters favored the Republican cause.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] Jefferson told the Baptists of Connecticut that there should be a "wall of separation" between church and state, alluding to the writings of Rhode Island's Roger Williams.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] Charles Cotesworth Pinckney successfully defended slavery at the Constitutional Convention and led the Federalist Party in the elections of 1804 and 1808.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] New York prior to 1799 and New Jersey prior to 1804 were slave states as well, and several leading northern Federalists from these states owned slaves, including John Jay and Philip Schuyler.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] Federalists supported the Fugitive Slave Act of 1793's nearly unanimous passage through Congress, and the Federalist-aligned administration of George Washington signed the bill into law.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] Rufus King was a prominent opponent of slavery and became the final Federalist presidential candidate in 1816.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] The Federalist Party is currently undergoing a renaissance among historians of the early Republic.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] This development is based largely on their occasional criticism of slavery.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] As the Democratic Republicans' stock has fallen in response to rising concerns over their leader Thomas Jefferson's racial views and deep entanglement with slavery, the Federalists who denounced Jefferson, the Republicans, and democracy itself have begun to look much better in comparison.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] While it has long been known that certain Federalist leaders—notably Alexander Hamilton and John Jay—opposed slavery and that attacks on slaveholding Virginia nabobs were part of the Federalist rhetorical arsenal after 1800, recent historians have found new significance in these facts.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] However, Day argues that concerns about the political weight of the slaveholding states were more significant than moral opposition to slavery.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] The Federalists were conscious of the need to boost voter identification with their party.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] Elections remained of central importance, but the rest of the political calendar was filled with celebrations, parades, festivals, and visual sensationalism.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] The Federalists employed multiple festivities, exciting parades, and even quasi-religious pilgrimages and "sacred" days that became incorporated into the American civil religion.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] George Washington was always their hero and after his death he became viewed as a sort of demigod looking down from heaven to bestow his blessings on the party.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] At first, the Federalists focused on commemorating the ratification of the Constitution and organized parades to demonstrate widespread popular support for the new Federalist Party.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] The parade organizers incorporated secular versions of traditional religious themes and rituals, thereby fostering a highly visible celebration of the nation's new civil religion.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] The Fourth of July became a semi-sacred day—a status it has maintained for much of American history.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] Its celebration in Boston emphasized national over local patriotism and included orations, dinners, militia musters, parades, marching bands, floats and fireworks.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] By 1800, the Fourth of July was closely identified with the Federalist Party.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] Republicans were annoyed and staged their own celebrations on the same day—with rival parades sometimes clashing with each other, which generated even more excitement and larger crowds.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] After the collapse of the Federalists starting in 1815, the Fourth of July became a nonpartisan holiday.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] The spoils system helped finance Federalist printers until 1801 and Republican editors after that.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] Federalist Postmasters General, Timothy Pickering (1791–94) and Joseph Habersham (1795–1801) appointed and removed local postmasters to maximize party funding.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] Numerous printers were appointed as postmasters.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] They did not deliver the mail, but they did collect fees from mail users and obtained free delivery of their own newspapers and business mail.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] To strengthen their coalitions and hammer away constantly at the opposition, both parties sponsored newspapers in the capital (Philadelphia) and other major cities.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] On the Republican side, Philip Freneau and Benjamin Franklin Bache blasted the administration with all the scurrility at their command.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] Bache in particular targeted Washington himself as the front man for monarchy who must be exposed.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] The Federalists, with twice as many newspapers at their command, slashed back with equal vituperation.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] John Fenno and "Peter Porcupine" (William Cobbett) were their nastiest penmen and Noah Webster their most learned.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] The Federalists never held a caucus or made a formal nomination.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] King received 34 votes from Federalist unpledged electors.
[src:1798-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-jersey/federalist-party-p02] Though the Federalists did not put forward a ticket in the 1820 election, Federalist presidential electors received a portion of the popular vote.
